Seek medical attention when you experience signs & symptoms such as:
Fever/severe headache

Drowsiness
Rash
Seizures
Muscle pain
Stiff neck etc.

#OnThisDay #OneYearOn
So far Britain has prevented mutations spreading like wildfire across the population, but concern remains

The @CovidGenomicsUK team at @CLESUniofExeter just started sequencing their 100th batch of COVID19 genomes. Our lab team has never been bigger than 3 people balancing childcare, home schooling and other responsibilities.

Since March 2020, we've sequenced >5000 genomes from local hospitals and lighthouse labs. I couldn't be prouder of what we've achieved. It's been a privilege to work alongside the other members of @CovidGenomicsUK and to do our bit in these challenging times.

Make sure not to give up too early. More appointment were added after about 10 minutes. Best practice would be to at least wait for my “appointments are gone” alert. It’s not perfect, but it’s a start!
The BCNJ vaccine website is near identical and this tip most certainly applies. These sites are clunky & confusing. I hope this helps, even a little.

originalTweet.text: UCNJ vaccine website tip: If you make it to this webpage, DO NOT LEAVE. It may have a loading circle for a long time. You can refresh the webpage safely until you see the dropdown to choose an appointment.

Big Announcement

I'm back online!

I will tweet whenever I detect there are appointments on the Bergen County vaccine site. Please be patient  — I'm using a new approach and might make some mistakes.

Thank you so much to everyone who reached out with any advice, tips & guidance.

And a huge, HUGE shoutout to @nj_vaccine who has been incredibly supportive and instrumental in this effort. This would not have been possible without your help. Thank you for your amazing work!

Continue to stay tuned, I will hopefully have a big update soon!

In the meantime, please follow @nj_vaccine — they are doing amazing work and are tracking an insane amount of locations in NJ (CVS, Rite Aid, Bergen County (!!), etc.) Please help spread the word!

Well, it's finally happened.

Bergen County has put a CAPTCHA on the BCNJ Vax website to prevent bots like me from checking available appointments. I will not be reporting on availability for the time being.

Stay tuned for updates, hopefully we can resolve this soon.

tweets.text:

originalTweet.text:
On May 4, 2020 Ducey lifted AZ's stay at home order letting all businesses open w/o mitigation or enforcement.

Simultaneously, @drcarachrist told the UA/ASU modeling team to stop their work & return all data.

Here's our blog post from that fateful day: http://azpha.org/wills-blog/2020/5/5/adhs-disbands-arizonas-covid-19-modeling-working-group…

tweets.text:
"We are the ones we've been waiting for." @HandmaidsOnHulu #ElisabethMoss @BradleyWhitford 

That's what @MarkedByCovid is all about. Survivors & victims' families raising hell for them & us. https://nbcnews.com/think/amp/ncna1266038…

P.S. Line coined by Black poets @alicewalker44 & #JuneJordan

Beyond honored to have helped bring the invisible grief of those #MarkedByCOVID into the light.

Yesterday I was tired, but the gratitude rolling in today from those relieved to finally see their perspective in print has revived me.

originalTweet.text:
All. Of. This. 

#Covid is by no means over. For those of us grieving loss, it'll never be over. twitter.com/MarkedByCovid/…

Healing America after #Covid19 ... has to mean fixing what went so terribly wrong and making up for the ways in which it did. We who were #MarkedByCOVID still need help — even if it's not as much fun to think about as a family barbecue. w/@covidgrief 

https://nbcnews.com/think/amp/ncna1266038…

tweets.text:
This is the look of 10 months of #COVID loss. The pain is unbearable.

And I'm a "lucky" one. You know my story. You know my father's name. We have each other.

I stay up at night haunted by the millions of people who think they are alone in this.

Those who don't know where to channel their rage. Those who don't have the support of family.

@MarkedByCOVID has saved my life. We need your financial support to ensure we can continue helping others. Can I count on you to chip in $15/month to help?
#MarkedByCOVID

originalTweet.text: For multiple days w #COVID19 on a vent, the mother kept pointing at her stomach, confused about whether or not she was still pregnant. We & the maternal-fetal team gently held her hand & showed her pictures of her stillborn baby in a white gown so she could process her grief. twitter.com/WesElyMD/statu…

tweets.text:
Co-founder @kdurquiza is dreading her 1st birthday w/out her dad and is hoping to surround herself with #MarkedByCCOVID community to fill the void & raise $40k by her 40th. 

Help nourish her spirit & keep the #COVIDjustice movement going. 

DONATE NOW: http://MarkedByCOVID.com/40x40

He died 10 months ago today. She was sick too but survived.

Last night I dreamt over-and-over that she was dying. The cause? Delayed impacts of COVID.

When will the suffering end? People @MarkedByCovid need support now.

Do you agree? RT+Sign. http://bit.ly/MBC_5Rs

Congratulations on 200 Million shots, America. But we must make we bring the shots to the people who need them most: Latinx, Black, Indigenous folks. 

#equity #100DaysWithBiden

Last week was the worst of the pandemic to date, with over 5.2 million new cases globally.

Yet the U.S. is sitting on millions of doses of Astra Zeneca vaccine that we haven’t approved for use (and almost certainly won’t need) while the rest of the world scrambles for supply.
No procedures have been made available to the public. There is no transparency.

Story time. Sometimes when I’m feeling time, I remember seeing @kdurquiza on the DNC. Just a few weeks after losing dad. She was a stranger to me, but it was the first time I felt like someone really understood what I was going through. I watched her and I felt seen.
we must go to the people

originalTweet.text: Where we saw success w/testing, especially in areas like I teach (85037/85353), is when local gov't was able to step in & secure sites that were easy to access for comm. members e.g. Town Halls, Parks, Schools. I think in order to cast a wider net, these need to be options.

29/

Finally, if the virus is airborne, health and care workers in infectious settings should be supplied with higher-grade PPE including respirator masks for ALL activities. There are several ongoing court cases. I predict the HCWs will win. 
28/

If the virus is spread mainly by the airborne route, we need to
-Encourage people to go outdoors
-Pay attention to ventilation (don’t use air-con)
-Reduce time spent indoors
-Avoid crowds
-Keep physical distance
-Wear well-fitting, high-quality masks whenever indoors
27/

We have a humanitarian emergency. WHO is the leading international organisation for health. It’s still pussyfooting on the question of airborne transmission. Based on current WHO guidance, many HCWs around the world are being denied high-grade PPE.
26/

People advising the WHO, and some who claim to speak for WHO, are saying this is all “nuance”, and we should “stop fighting each other” and that aerosol scientists are “trying to further their own careers”. This is gaslighting.
25/

World Health Organisation got it wrong back in March 2020. They rejected the advice of aerosol scientists offered a year ago. They’re now saying that aerosol transmission “can occur in certain situations”, by which they mean (mostly) medical AGPs. 
24/

Smell the garlic on someone’s breath. You don’t want to be close to them do you? But you can still smell it across the room. Washing your hands won’t help here. Scrubbing surfaces won’t help. But opening the window will.
23/

So talking about “close-range” transmission confuses two different modes of transmission. Yes, we need to keep physical distance. No, that’s not only (or even mainly) to reduce droplet transmission, it’s to reduce AIRBORNE transmission.
22/

A key point: “close-range” is not a route of transmission. We all know the virus is transmitted mostly through close contact. AEROSOLS are transmitted mainly by close contact, but they ALSO travel longer distances in the air.
21/

Here’s a previous thread by my co-author @jljcolorado which goes into more detail on some of the science:

tweets.text:
EVIDENCE #10: ABSENCE OF EVIDENCE THAT OTHER ROUTES OF TRANSMISSION ARE DOMINANT. The evidence for droplet or fomite transmission is weak. These routes likely occur but unlikely to be *dominant*.
https://thelancet.com/journals/laninf/article/PIIS1473-3099(20)30561-2/fulltext…
18/

EVIDENCE #9: ABSENCE OF DISCONFIRMING STUDIES. We looked hard, and we didn’t find a SINGLE study which offered evidence against airborne transmission. If airborne transmission didn’t happen, it would surely not be too hard to “disprove” it? 
17/

EVIDENCE #8: TRANSMISSION BETWEEN CAGED FERRETS VIA AIR DUCTS. Yes I know, “animal models”. But this isn’t a claim that human physiology is same as ferret physiology. It’s saying *the only way this could have happened* is AIRBORNE.
https://nature.com/articles/s41467-021-21918-6…
16/

EVIDENCE #7: SARS-COV-2 FOUND IN AIR DUCTS. In a hospital, the virus is sucked out in the ventilation system and cultured from the ducts and filters. There’s only one way it could have got there: AIRBORNE.  
https://nature.com/articles/s41598-020-76442-2…
15/

Same team (Lednicky et al—these people are the *world experts* on capturing airborne viruses) also isolated SARS-CoV-2 virus from clinic rooms:
https://ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7792982/…
14/

EVIDENCE #6: VIABLE VIRUS HAS BEEN FOUND IN AIR. It’s hard to catch airborne virus so not all studies are positive—but the black swan has been seen, not once but several times. eg this study of virus in a CAR.
https://sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1201971221003751…
13/

Indeed, in that case, the judge accused the so-called expert of using "false arguments" and "fallacies", and another expert for being unaware of key scientific developments in his field when testifying. 
12/

There has been at least one successful court case where healthcare workers successfully sued their employer for providing inadequate PPE. The judge considered the evidence in support of airborne spread to be overwhelming. 
http://citoyens.soquij.qc.ca/php/decision.php?ID=ABCD408A9BC8D0D4410C2217C6237358&captchaToken=03AGdBq27PF3HxvtopL3UsBP-fuPjz4Bfc3fL-ts8BFYIOxlqi0kT0wqEa6pkgAP-aeI7S6GAStTHhcaN8GsKr-edn2ZAKQjg5EfebyEBpgaHHaLysEMYvMeO1MIKeG8MPE-H7ThipMB7MUrR_djL3BVjcVGKc-_Bp9h4Ru-1pWBo1O5u9NO9GGKhQX38VxkdhB_hekVuqRPEo630DZeTfwrJJIxC_TR-wrD6l8N6gZ51JcUkTxFJcY_Ns7GAoJ6k5ZikbCyweUK-JWYflfEvxapMoyGC_VEkA2ioWfe3R9sKQMQUu3WPQZG5hplh5XfqeAmA5ydcoM9SZJxMtuUuGlgj-JNc1TY_V1fHcdjeoEDEqAp58s9m6ts00VzNgzjRVN9IsRZt-EfI87ER64JZJBeZL-uIrwbvedWCCCERVmqIekEi7McaBntfsdtn_Ln4qEBqQr3hEnVvAmlm168N7uUcirKhizDzpO9CYUSRtrIB6W-rDP2U7-MyDiM-pzKnCLDmNMc3mkgHitYfjury4y-jeYt9hRmIqqsXLF3yjsawLfUcIV9nYthg… 
11/

EVIDENCE #5: HEALTHCARE WORKERS GET INFECTED DESPITE MEDICAL MASKS. Despite standard-grade PPE (which protects against droplets but not fully against aerosols), HCWs develop *occupational* Covid-19.
https://acpjournals.org/doi/full/10.7326/M20-7567…
10/

EVIDENCE #4: TRANSMISSION ALMOST ALWAYS OCCURS INDOORS. If the virus were spread mainly by droplets (a gravity-driven process), indoor and outdoor transmission would be similar at comparable separation. But they’re not.
https://academic.oup.com/jid/article/223/4/550/6009483…
9/

https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamanetworkopen/fullarticle/2774707…

मैं नाकामयाब प्रधानमंत्री बोलूँगी, तुम मोदी समझ लेना ।

भाजपा मुख्यालय में आज सिंघु व टिकरी बॉर्डर की तुलना जैसे मरकज़ से की गई, दलाल बोबड़े भी अंबाडानी की भाषा बोलने लगा । अन्यायपालिका में अभी इतना दम नहीं कि वो किसानों से पंगा लेकर बच सके, ट्रैक्टर उधर चल देंगे #TractorMarchDelhi

The @UKHouseofLords is now prorogued, ahead of the State Opening of Parliament on 11 May. Until then, you can catch up on all of the Committee's work on our website:

Missed our session last week on the long-term impact the pandemic might have on parents and families? You can watch it back at http://parliamentlive.tv or read the transcript on our website. Here’s just a few clips to give you a flavour of what we heard (1/5)
Sally Hogg from @ParentInfantFdn spoke about the impact on babies and infants and the support that’s needed to mitigate the long-term negative consequences (4/5)
Finally, here’s David Holmes from @family_action on the action he’d like to see from Government (5/5)
A reminder that tomorrow we continue to explore the long-term impact of the pandemic on parents and families (1/2)
You can watch the session live from 0945, or on catch up, here: https://parliamentlive.tv/Event/Index/774856c9-048b-4834-80ea-9788729c0296… (2/2)

'Some people are choosing between data and food.'

Martha Lane Fox, chair of Lords COVID-19 Committee, calls the government to provide cheaper access to the internet for those who are receiving benefits.

 http://app.times.radio/listen

@MattChorley | @Marthalanefox | @HLCOVID19Com
We're really pleased to be at the APPG on #TacklingLoneliness this afternoon with @RedCrossPolicy to talk about our report's findings on the impact of digitalisation on social connections.
We’ve shared our report with the UK Government and asked them to respond. We’ll let you know when we hear back. (8/8)

Today we’ve published the report of our inquiry into the rapid acceleration of digital trends that has taken place during the pandemic. Read the report here: https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/154007/government-should-consider-new-health-and-employment-rights-to-protect-wellbeing-in-the-digital-world/… (1/8)

In the last year,we’ve seen massive acceleration in all sorts of digital trends–online shopping,remote working,digitalised health&public services…We’ve looked at the long-term impact for health&wellbeing,work lives,education&relationships,&tomorrow we publish our findings(1/6)
We heard how it’s transforming jobs in retail (5/6)
And here’s @TomJohnFoley on the implication for digital healthcare (6/6)

A reminder that tomorrow we'll be holding the first of our evidence sessions into the impact of the pandemic on parents and families: https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/153859/committee-investigates-longterm-impact-of-pandemic-on-parents-and-families/… (1/2)
Tune in here to watch from 0945am: https://parliamentlive.tv/Event/Index/30bc8d6c-b22a-4c2c-8b7d-b08db36e6359… (2/2)

On Tuesday, we'll be holding the first evidence session of our short inquiry into the long-term impact of the pandemic on parents and families https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/153859/committee-investigates-longterm-impact-of-pandemic-on-parents-and-families/… (1/2)
Tune in from 0945am when we'll be hearing from @raceequality @ParentInfantFdn @family_action @SHSorguk and @magpieprojectuk You can watch the session on http://parliamentlive.tv (2/2)

Since October we have been hearing evidence about the relationship between COVID-19, increasing digitalisation and our social and economic wellbeing. Having now considered all the evidence, our #BeyondDigital report will be published on 21 April.

The @UKHouseofLords breaks for the Easter recess today, returning on 12 April. In the meantime, here's some highlights from the meeting we had on Tuesday, looking at how governments could make improving wellbeing a driver for policy decisions (1/7)
And Marie Brousseau-Navarro from @futuregencymru told us about the legislation that had been introduced in Wales (6/7)
She also explained what that has meant in practice for how policy making has changed (7/7)

Tomorrow at 945 am, we'll be asking, in light of the pandemic, do governments need to put greater emphasis on social and environmental contributors to wellbeing, as well as economic growth, when determining policy? https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/152880/how-can-governments-use-wellbeing-measures-in-making-and-evaluating-policy-decisions/… (1/2)
You can watch our session live, or on catch up, here: https://parliamentlive.tv/Event/Index/daab5ba8-5c44-455a-b7ea-06dc6c741870… (2/2)

On Tuesday, we'll be looking at whether the pandemic could result in governments placing a greater emphasis on improving wellbeing as a measure of success https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/152880/how-can-governments-use-wellbeing-measures-in-making-and-evaluating-policy-decisions/… (1/2)

From 0945, we'll be hearing from @futuregencymru @jedeneve @OECD and @CarnegieUKTrust about models that offer alternatives to GDP and examples of wellbeing approaches to policy making being pursued in different countries (2/2)

Back in October, we launched an inquiry into how digital trends accelerated by the pandemic might impact on our physical and mental health, social interactions and work lives in the years ahead: https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/news/120355/committee-asks-what-increasingly-digital-lives-will-mean-for-our-wellbeing/… (1/2)

While we're busy writing up the report of our inquiry, you can read through all the written evidence we received, and the transcripts of all our oral evidence sessions, on our website: https://committees.parliament.uk/committee/460/covid19-committee/publications/… (2/2)
Did you know that you can catch up on any of our previous evidence sessions (or those of any other Parliamentary committee) at http://Parliamentlive.TV? https://parliamentlive.tv/Committees

Given many pupils are returning to school today, we thought it would be timely to share a reminder of some of the evidence we heard last month about how the move to online learning over the last year might affect children and young people in the long-term (1/5)
Natalie Perera from @EduPolicyInstitute gave us her recommendations for the action needed from Government to help pupils catch up (4/5)
And finally, here is @MargaretMulhol2 with her vision of how education could be different in future (5/5)

1/3 PREVENT THE SPREAD:

For anyone going out today to leaflet about your support group, remember these important tips. 

1. Only leaflet if you're feeling well
2. Remember social distancing and avoid leafleting in groups/physical contact with others.

3/3.

As the situation changes, advice on hygiene and approach will develop too. Please check the latest updates before providing care each day. 

Supporting the most vulnerable means preventing the spread and keeping each other safe.

2/3

3.wash your hands before and after (and ideally sanitise during)
4. think about wearing gloves
5. don't lick your fingers to separate pieces of paper

More guidance on hygiene and Covid aid here: https://queercare.network/our-work/resources/covid-19/…

1/3 We're continuing to develop resources for local groups to be able to deliver mutual aid and community care in a safe way. For the meantime https://facebook.com/CovidAidUK/ is the best place for up to date info.

SECURITY AND PERSONAL DATA:

Do NOT pass on personal data from volunteers & those requesting help to anyone, especially other organisations or institutions.

This is both for legal reasons & also to protect vulnerable people who might not be safe if you share their details.

This includes making sure you do not pass on information to your local council or government body. Your council can support your group without needing to know specifics of who you are supporting directly.

You don't have to start a local group to support your community.

Popping a friendly note through the door of your neighbour offering a supportive ear can be just as effective.

Q: How quickly will we get to more doctor’s offices getting vaccines? How about walk up appointments?

A: Both of these are already happening in some areas. We still need to keep our community vaccination clinics going. So we will continue evaluating and changing as needed.
Moving to more community based vaccinations will allow more people to be vaccinated because it will be more convenient, but the rate of people getting vaccinated will be slower.
The more we see people not take precautions, the more spread we will see.

Q: Can variants get kids sick more?

A: We know some variants are more transmissible. In Michigan, they are seeing an increase of children being hospitalized and the primary variant of concern there is the U.K. variant.
What we will see is more mobile clinics, in addition to more walk up vaccine clinics.

Originally, we required that all doses were used within 7 days to encourage speed. That requirement is going away to allow for more flexibility and more doses at smaller facilities and doctors’ offices.

Q: Is there more outreach going to those places that aren’t using allocation?

A: We have been doing that. Targeted messages have been sent to those communities. And our high throughput coalition helps to reallocate doses to areas where they are needed.

Q: Why does the Hispanic community have lower percentage of vaccinated people?

A: Access is one reason, for sure. We are working to make vaccines more available. Some haven’t trusted the vaccine yet so we are working to educate them on the vaccines’ efficacy.

Q: Is there any indication why 16-24 year olds are lagging behind older age groups in vaccinations?

A: This is typical across the U.S. Remember there’s a collective protection we all have when we get vaccinated. Many schools are hosting vaccine clinics to help those age groups.

If we want to prevent a resurgence, we need to get vaccinated. 

Vaccines are safe and we have only seen a very small number of people who have become infected with COVID after getting the vaccine.

So far, our vaccines are more than 99% effective at preventing infections.
Everyone else can be vaccinated to protect those who cannot be vaccinated yet.

Dr. Dunn:

Of course, this is nothing like back in December when 41.8% of our ICU beds were people with COVID. But it should be a reality check for us that we’re NOT done with this yet.

People are still being hospitalized and ending up in the ICU with COVID-19. Currently, 12.1% of our ICU beds have a COVID-positive case. A week ago, the 7-day average was 11.5%. A month ago the average was 10.6%.

This is the largest number of counties we’ve had in low transmission since we started the transmission index and the first time we have more low counties than moderate since we really started seeing recovery in February.

Transmission index
This week our Transmission Index is still showing an improving situation. Beaver, Duchesne, and Morgan counties moved from moderate to low. We now have (1) county in high, (12) in moderate and (16) in low transmission.
And in the meantime, there are plenty of other options out there right now for getting vaccinated if you are initially turned down and want to go in a different direction.

We hope this effort will jump start an entirely new wave of demand among an entirely new population.
